We scheduled a private event for 15 guests through Art Room Events on Saturday from 6:30 to 10:00 pm. I will acknowledge that I am not a sports person and did not realize that this was during a Final Four game, but no one mentioned that this would be a bad time for a private event when the reservation was made. Otherwise, we could have chosen a different time or a different venue, and certainly would have done so if we knew the service would be so awful.  Five of us arrived at 6:15 to get the room set up for the remaining guests. We went to the small lobby area and stood between two signs that said, "Wait Here to Be Seated." There were two servers feverishly pecking orders into the computer system, a blonde and a brunette. Neither one looked up or acknowledged us for several long minutes. When we finally got the blonde server's attention and said we were there for a private event, she just looked at us like a deer in headlights. She whipped out a calendar, quickly thumbed through and found that we did in fact have a reservation. But the private room we were supposed to have was being used for other customers. She had to find a place to put us. We remained in the designated "Wait Here to Be Seated Area" while she disappeared.  While we were waiting, additional guests for our party arrived, as well as other customers. So the small lobby area was becoming quite crowded. The brunette server, who was passing from the outdoor patio to the bar, very loudly and rudely yelled at us, "YOU CAN'T STAND IN THIS HALLWAY! YOU NEED TO MOVE! YOU NEED TO KEEP THIS AREA CLEAR!" Not once, not twice, but three times. There was never a polite, "Please excuse me, I need to get through" to preface this. She was immediately very aggressive and belligerent. We said we'd love to move if she'd simply tell us where we could go. No response. Again, we were standing precisely where it says, "Wait Here to Be Seated."  Finally, more than a half hour later, and well after our 6:30 reserved time, a small room was cleared for us. It was about a 10' x 12' room, with a few small tables and chairs and a fireplace. For 15 people, it was so cramped and standing room only. And HOT! We could barely move, and there was barely any room to set up the party accessories. The event was interactive and required us to mix, mingle, and move around. Drinks were spilled, glassware was broken, but we literally could not move without bumping into something. My vintage purse and coat were soaked when someone bumped a table and spilled some drinks on a chair.  We intended to order food for the event, but we could barely get the server to stand still long enough to get drink orders, let alone order food. I did manage to order some appetizers about 90 minutes into the event, but there really was no great place to set them up, and no plates, napkins, or flatware were provided. So guests really couldn't eat much. The one mozzarella stick and the small bit of spinach dip I tried were adequate, but not nearly sufficient.  Once our event concluded, we moved to the outdoor patio area (which was being served by the angry brunette server from before), with the intent of ordering more drinks and finally getting some food, but the server refused to come to our table. Nearby tables were ordering food and drinks and being served. Some members of our party went to the bar to fetch drinks, and after waiting for quite some time, a couple of people went across the street and brought back a huge bag of carryout sushi so we could finally eat. I know, I know: it's rude to carry food into a restaurant, but at this point, I was hangry and beyond caring about courtesy. We obviously weren't going to be getting any food here, and we didn't want to leave our drinks to go elsewhere.  Galway Arms could have made much, much more money on our group had the service been even marginally better than it was. This was a missed opportunity for the venue and certainly didn't make a good impression with any of our guests.

If you go to the Galway Arms to watch football and drink beer, then maybe this is a 4star venue. A traditional Irish pub, a little too dark inside but compensated for sure by a large deck at the front with ample seating. However if your main objective is great food and service then it's a 3 star at best. The menu is what you would expect from an American based Irish pub - burgers, fries, salads mixed in with shepherd's pie, fish and chips, Irish stew. But the service is somewhat chaotic (charming to some). Several very young waiters and waitresses, some actually from Galway, but clearly unable to cope at peak times and not even sure of which table to take the food to. I wouldn't expect this level of service in an "American restaurant / bar" but maybe they think that expats will be fond of remembering the service levels back home (including the UK). Apparently the burger and the monster sandwich are good, but my chicken breast sandwich was distinctively average. So in summary, beers and football - YES, but maybe eat someplace else !

An old, established spot in Lincoln Park, the Galway Arms has a vibrant bar and also a number of dining areas. The vestiges of the old house that was the basis for this structure is apparent in the architecture which is charming. The rooms can be a bit small for the number of tables, and it sometimes is loud here, but it is, after all, an Irish-style place. The food is good and never disappointing. Service can vary, depending on the size of the crowd in the restaurant. Fish and chips are always good, especially during Lent when it's all you can eat. The sides that come with the fish and chips are never enough, since they ca be quite tasty. The burgers can be very generous, and they are particularly nice when offered as a special. Some of the sides are interesting, with parsnips that are not the usual one-dimensional way some serve this root vegetable. Wines are an option at the Galway, but the emphasis seems to be on beer. It is a busy place, and in warm weather, seating spills onto the patio in the front of the building. The bar is cozy, and some food items are offered late or, rather. later in the evening. It's good to have this place in the neighborhood, but it sometimes is a little raucous at the times you want to have a quiet meal, might even want to hear those with you speak. But that's more due to the crowd that comes here and not the polite and professional wait staff that do their best.

Great Irish pub! Great music!
This is a upscale local pub with several fireplaces to warm yourself up by

Chicago is replete with Irish bars, but in the pecking order of such bars, Galway surely must stand near the top.  It stands out by virtue of its great menu and spacious dining facilities (which include an awesome patio).  For those reasons, as well as Galway's convenient location and cozy interior, it's a great place to bring out of town guests.

It can sometimes be hard to find your own comfortable space in a typically-crowded Irish bar in Chicago, but not at Galway Arms. It’s enough off the beaten path to make it possible to avoid congestion. Like Fado, you’ll enjoy the fact that …
Great beer selection
Solid Irish bar. Great cozy atmosphere in the back.

Great burgers, good prices.  Came here for dinner and ordered a Guinness Burger preceded by Smoked Salmon as an appetizer.  I felt that the burger and the sweet potato fries I got along with it were quite good.  The smoked salmon appetizer was underwhelming though, where the bread and red "caviar" it came with left something to be desired.  Overall, I got a good impression of Galway Arms.

Fun Irish pub. It gets pretty lively on weekend nights. The food is tasty and reasonably priced, and they have a great beer list. The covered patio is great on a nice afternoon or evening. They also have plenty of indoor seating.

I like this place well enough. I really only sit outside and with the fire towers and being right on the street makes for a nice place to have some drinks during the day and through the night spring through fall.
Good craft beer selection and friendly staff. Food was delicious!
Awesome pub with some great food and drink
Fantastic food, young fun and friendly staff.
Good space, old pub!

If you could give 0 stars I would definitely oblige. My boyfriend (who is Korean) and I (which I am Black/African-American) came here on Saturday, September 6th which was my first time here, because we wanted a quick bite to eat. We were greeted by a young lady at 6:22p.m. and seated with our menus and given water by one guy all within 2 minutes. A great start right? Well, we made our menu selections and were ready to order, however no waitress or waiter approached our table after watching 3 of them go to nearby tables and patrons. The time that had lapsed was about 20 minutes and we knew that we would not get ANY service due to the blatant DISCRIMINATION being displayed. I sat and witnessed two different couples and a family (seated next to us) get seated within 5-15 minutes after us and within 6 minutes they each had their orders into the waitresses within a timely manner. In total over 30 minutes passed and we were NOT given any service or acknowledgement of our existence. This could have continued to go on for quite some time. It is truly sad that this happened and the manager(s) allow such acts to be displayed. I would NEVER return to this place NOR recommend anyone to go here! Their actions speak louder than words, so remember that.
Was not too impressed, but it is a great outside patio place.   The food was just average for me, but I would go back sometime.

This is your typical Irish Pub, that happens to have a nice outdoor patio and some "banquet" type rooms upstairs, including extra bars. Do go expecting a gourmet meal...standard bar food applies. But do go and get a Guiness is you're in Lincoln Park. It's fun during St. Patrick's Day.

Great outdoor area and a fairly descent craft beer menu.  Service was a bit slow and unorganized but given the crowds I could understand why this would be.  Didn't order anything off the main menu but did order a few apps that were spot on.  The location of the establishment also makes this a great place to start your evening and then move onto other establishments in the area.  Is definitely on my list for Saturday at 4pm.

I’ve lived within walking distance of Galway Arms for nearly 4 years now and never stopped in.  I’m a sucker for a good burger special, so when I spotted a sign for $5 burgers on Wednesdays, I decided to give it a chance.  The specials seem to change frequently, and the website doesn’t appear to have been updated any time recently.  For that reason, I can’t guarantee that special still exists, but, trust me, you’re not missing out.  To quote the late, great Rodney Dangerfield, this burger “still had marks where the jockey was hittin’ it.”   It tasted like a store brand frozen beef patty that sat in the back of fraternity house freezer for several years collecting freezer burn until someone uncovered it.  It’s really a shame when restaurants choose to use frozen over fresh.  It’s an even bigger shame when that restaurant has a beautiful patio in the heart of Lincoln Park.  I really wanted to like this burger given the price,the proximity to my apartment, and the terrific patio overlooking Clark Street, but this will likely go down as one of the worst burgers Chicago Burger Guide has ever experienced.
the food and drinks here is amazing! loved it i had the burger and it was exceptional loved it! the staff was friendly and very helpful and explained the menu very well! will go back there again!

I have dined in this restaurant twice and I would definately make the trip to go another time. The food is amazing and not overly expensive. The patio is gorgeous on a nice day and with a pint of Magners in your hand you cant go wrong. The pub a great Irish feel to it, a very enjoyable experience.
The galway arms is a super irish pub with friendly staff and a welcoming atmosphere! The food is second to none and I will definitely return for dinner before I leave Chicago!

Great Irish Pub!  I love the corn beef sandwich and the Shepard's Pie.  Both the inside decor with the fireplace and little alcoves to sit in, and the large outdoor patio make it a great place to hang out with friends.  Have also enjoyed the live Irish music on Sunday nights.

The outdoor heated patio is fabulous on those nice, yet chilly evenings.  Love the interior decor with the fireplaces and the cozy corners. Great drinks, excellent food. Definitely a fun place to hang out with some good friends and make new ones.
killer irish breakfast

Tip: *listen to this* Order the Guiness Stew! Best stew I have ever had. So worth it! Also, Fish Fry on Fridays are the best. Girlfriend and I went here on a random Friday night trying to find somewhere to watch the UCLA game back when they were in the PAc-12 championship game, and Galway catered to us! They actually took the time to change the channel on one of the tv's to the game we wanted. Great service, great food, and, O, did i mention they pour the best Guiness from tap?
Always receive very friendly and efficient service when we eat here. Enjoy the fish & chips and they have a great beer selection.
Very good beer selection that rotates quite often. And Barry is just charming and loveable.
Galway is one of my favorite bars in Chicago for craft beer. Great service and prices.
